46:54.000 --> 46:56.000
because we need to cover the information

46:56.000 --> 46:59.000
in some words, symbols or something else.

46:59.000 --> 47:01.000
And we don't always do it effectively,

47:01.000 --> 47:02.000
that is, to the full extent.

47:02.000 --> 47:03.000
What we want to convey,

47:03.000 --> 47:06.000
we can convey to a certain extent of credibility.

47:06.000 --> 47:08.000
Someone better, for example,

47:08.000 --> 47:11.000
uses the word cat, more vocabulary,

47:11.000 --> 47:13.000
those are more credible in transferring information.

47:13.000 --> 47:17.000
If a person does not have a very large vocabulary,

47:17.000 --> 47:19.000
or does not know some terms,

47:19.000 --> 47:21.000
naturally, he will do worse.

47:21.000 --> 47:24.000
Next, there is a transfer of information

47:24.000 --> 47:26.000
through communication channels.

47:26.000 --> 47:28.000
Each communication channel has its own rules

47:28.000 --> 47:31.000
by which we can encode this information.

47:31.000 --> 47:33.000
And again, there is a moment

47:33.000 --> 47:35.000
that if I know these rules well,

47:35.000 --> 47:39.000
I know well, I will lose less credibility of information.

47:39.000 --> 47:41.000
If I don't know the rules very well,

47:41.000 --> 47:45.000
I can lose this information at this stage.

47:45.000 --> 47:47.000
Next, there is decoding of information.

47:47.000 --> 47:53.000
Again, a person begins to decode information

47:53.000 --> 47:56.000
by passing it through his own filters.

47:56.000 --> 47:59.000
And the filters start from the settings

47:59.000 --> 48:02.000
and end with some purely physical effects on him.

48:02.000 --> 48:05.000
If, for example, he does it in a calm environment,

48:05.000 --> 48:08.000
then he perceives the information more reliably.

48:09.000 --> 48:12.000
If his emotional level is higher,

48:12.000 --> 48:14.000
then it is also a filter.

48:14.000 --> 48:17.000
There are a lot of filters here,

48:17.000 --> 48:20.000
but they are mostly understood in the course of communication,

48:20.000 --> 48:22.000
effective communication.

48:22.000 --> 48:25.000
There is more information about filters.

48:25.000 --> 48:29.000
The thing is that there is a difference between noise and interference.

48:29.000 --> 48:33.000
It is present at every stage of information processing.

48:33.000 --> 48:39.000
Since we are talking about the topic of information processing technology,

48:39.000 --> 48:44.000
we will be the addressees.

48:44.000 --> 48:47.000
We are the ones who receive information.

48:47.000 --> 48:51.000
How to make our work with information more effective?

48:51.000 --> 48:53.000
Slide 50.

48:53.000 --> 48:58.000
So, we will not talk about the single information we receive

48:58.000 --> 49:01.000
and its effectiveness.

49:01.000 --> 49:04.000
We can talk about information flows.

49:04.000 --> 49:05.000
Why?

49:05.000 --> 49:10.000
Because the big problem of modernity

49:10.000 --> 49:13.000
is the huge amount of information.

49:13.000 --> 49:16.000
A huge amount of information is being thrown at us.

49:16.000 --> 49:20.000
I want to make a lyrical digression.

49:20.000 --> 49:26.000
We can classify information in this way.

49:26.000 --> 49:31.000
We can classify it in a negative and positive way.

49:31.000 --> 49:35.000
This is very clearly highlighted in modern society.

49:35.000 --> 49:37.000
It becomes a big problem.

49:37.000 --> 49:38.000
Why?

49:38.000 --> 49:42.000
Because a person has a threshold of sensitivity.

49:42.000 --> 49:44.000
Any of us has it.

49:44.000 --> 49:48.000
When too much negative information comes through this threshold,

49:48.000 --> 49:51.000
we cannot cope with it psychologically.

49:51.000 --> 50:00.000
This negative information starts to affect us negatively.

50:00.000 --> 50:03.000
We get a lot of stress from it.

50:03.000 --> 50:08.000
In modern society, when there are big disadvantages,

50:08.000 --> 50:10.000
there are big advantages.

50:10.000 --> 50:11.000
And vice versa.

50:11.000 --> 50:15.000
When there are big advantages, there are always big limitations.

50:15.000 --> 50:19.000
I have already said that information is a powerful weapon.

50:20.000 --> 50:23.000
On the other hand, it is a weak point of any person.

50:23.000 --> 50:25.000
If there is a lot of information about me,

50:25.000 --> 50:27.000
I do not know how to control it.

50:27.000 --> 50:29.000
How to control this process?

50:29.000 --> 50:33.000
The same is true of the amount of information we receive from outside.

50:33.000 --> 50:36.000
On the one hand, this is a great benefit,

50:36.000 --> 50:39.000
because it allows us to navigate in time and space,

50:39.000 --> 50:42.000
to make effective decisions,

50:42.000 --> 50:45.000
because we receive the right amount of information.

50:45.000 --> 50:47.000
On the other hand, information affects us.

50:48.000 --> 50:50.000
If we receive negative information,

50:50.000 --> 50:54.000
it affects us in a destructive way.

50:54.000 --> 51:01.000
It drives us into stress.

51:01.000 --> 51:05.000
The amount of information that we receive is very stressful.

51:05.000 --> 51:14.000
The human brain has the ultimate ability to digest information.

51:14.000 --> 51:19.000
Psychologists recommend one thing.

51:19.000 --> 51:21.000
To protect yourself from negative information.

51:21.000 --> 51:25.000
Do not listen to the radio, do not watch TV,

51:25.000 --> 51:27.000
do not read the newspaper before lunch.

51:27.000 --> 51:30.000
Do you remember the story of the dog's heart?

51:30.000 --> 51:32.000
Do not read the Soviet newspapers before lunch.

51:32.000 --> 51:33.000
And there are no other newspapers.

51:33.000 --> 51:35.000
So, do not read the newspaper at all.

51:36.000 --> 51:45.000
Studies have shown that students in England

51:45.000 --> 51:47.000
were affected by the amount of negative information

51:47.000 --> 51:50.000
that we receive every day from the news.

51:50.000 --> 51:54.000
They really got sick from this information.

51:54.000 --> 52:00.000
Therefore, the importance of information is now very...

52:00.000 --> 52:02.000
By the way, we do not notice this.

52:02.000 --> 52:07.000
The biggest drawback is that we do not notice it.

52:07.000 --> 52:09.000
For us, this huge flow of information,

52:09.000 --> 52:11.000
which we pass through ourselves all the time,

52:11.000 --> 52:14.000
is a norm.

52:14.000 --> 52:17.000
We work with it.

52:17.000 --> 52:19.000
We are forced to receive a lot of information

52:19.000 --> 52:21.000
in order to make effective decisions.

52:21.000 --> 52:24.000
But we do not realize that this is a really stress-generating factor.

52:24.000 --> 52:27.000
And if there is an opportunity,

52:27.000 --> 52:31.000
it is better to dose the flow of information

52:31.000 --> 52:34.000
that comes to you from the outside

52:34.000 --> 52:36.000
and which you have to process.

52:36.000 --> 52:38.000
But this is a lyrical retreat.

52:38.000 --> 52:43.000
Unfortunately, we will not get rid of negative information at all.

52:43.000 --> 52:47.000
But we must understand that positive information

52:47.000 --> 52:53.000
is much more important for us than negative.

52:53.000 --> 52:59.000
We must try to compensate for the negative with positive.

52:59.000 --> 53:02.000
So, let's get back to our business life,

53:02.000 --> 53:05.000
to our modern information flows.

53:05.000 --> 53:11.000
There are several phenomena of modern information flows.

53:11.000 --> 53:14.000
In particular, progress in the field of information production

53:14.000 --> 53:17.000
leads to a decrease in the general level of information.

53:17.000 --> 53:20.000
And it generates new types of network services.

53:20.000 --> 53:22.000
What does this mean?

53:22.000 --> 53:25.000
Look, there is a lot of information.

53:25.000 --> 53:28.000
The growth is rapid and sharp.

53:28.000 --> 53:31.000
But we have less information.

53:31.000 --> 53:33.000
Why?

53:33.000 --> 53:36.000
Because our body is protected.

53:36.000 --> 53:39.000
We have more filters.

53:39.000 --> 53:42.000
We just let some information pass by our ears

53:42.000 --> 53:44.000
and do not react to it in any way.

53:44.000 --> 53:50.000
And by the way, at this moment we can miss some very important information.

53:51.000 --> 53:54.000
Such an disproportionate growth of unstructured information

53:54.000 --> 53:57.000
leads to its poor structuring.

53:57.000 --> 53:59.000
What is unstructured information?

53:59.000 --> 54:03.000
This is information that cannot be a tool.

54:03.000 --> 54:04.000
It cannot be.

54:04.000 --> 54:06.000
It needs to be structured.

54:06.000 --> 54:08.000
It is necessary to spend a large amount of effort

54:08.000 --> 54:11.000
to structure this unstructured information.

54:11.000 --> 54:16.000
A lot of parasite information appears.

54:16.000 --> 54:19.000
We do not need it at all.

54:19.000 --> 54:23.000
But we let it in and process it.

54:23.000 --> 54:28.000
And it is an obstacle for us.

54:28.000 --> 54:31.000
Next.

54:31.000 --> 54:36.000
Disagreement with the formal information is a real necessity.

54:36.000 --> 54:40.000
But to choose what we really need from this sea of information

54:40.000 --> 54:45.000
is also a separate job that requires resources.

54:45.000 --> 54:48.000
And there is also duplication of information.

54:48.000 --> 54:51.000
The same message is published in different places.

54:51.000 --> 54:54.000
But we need to open it and see.

54:54.000 --> 54:55.000
I have already read it.

54:55.000 --> 54:59.000
It is also a waste of time and resources.

54:59.000 --> 55:01.000
This is the first phenomenon.

55:01.000 --> 55:02.000
Slide number 51.

55:02.000 --> 55:04.000
The second phenomenon.

55:04.000 --> 55:09.000
New network services, sometimes with a thousand times less sources,

55:09.000 --> 55:12.000
solve the problem of consumers much more effectively.

55:12.000 --> 55:13.000
Why?

55:14.000 --> 55:23.000
Large network search systems have come to the conclusion

55:23.000 --> 55:30.000
that network integration of news is necessary.

55:30.000 --> 55:34.000
They have concluded agreements with the largest information agencies

55:34.000 --> 55:41.000
and began to provide news information to these agencies online.

55:41.000 --> 55:43.000
You do not need to buy newspapers.

55:43.000 --> 55:47.000
You can open the Internet and read all the news.

55:47.000 --> 55:50.000
But what happens here?

55:50.000 --> 55:53.000
On the one hand, it seems to be a plus.

55:53.000 --> 55:57.000
And on the other hand, it turns out to be a one-sided coverage of news.

55:57.000 --> 55:59.000
And here you need to choose all the time

55:59.000 --> 56:03.000
between the reliability of the information,

56:03.000 --> 56:08.000
its objectivity and its volume.

56:08.000 --> 56:10.000
It is proportional.

56:10.000 --> 56:15.000
The less we cover the sources, the more subjectivity increases.

56:15.000 --> 56:17.000
The next phenomenon.

56:17.000 --> 56:19.000
Slide number 52.

56:19.000 --> 56:22.000
The existing today mechanism of news integration

56:22.000 --> 56:27.000
is effective only when there is an information service within the company.

56:27.000 --> 56:29.000
What is this phenomenon?

56:29.000 --> 56:31.000
This is a phenomenon that there is a lot of information.

56:32.000 --> 56:37.000
In order to get reliable, verified,

56:37.000 --> 56:40.000
analytically structured information,

56:40.000 --> 56:45.000
we need a service in the company that will do this.

56:45.000 --> 56:48.000
We need employees who will sit and

56:48.000 --> 56:52.000
from this huge stream of information

56:52.000 --> 56:56.000
to make the necessary decision for us.

56:56.000 --> 56:58.000
Because here, again,

56:58.000 --> 57:02.000
we have this ratio of volume of information

57:02.000 --> 57:04.000
and level of reliability.

57:04.000 --> 57:08.000
When we talk about unstructured information,

57:08.000 --> 57:14.000
if we reduce the volume,

57:14.000 --> 57:16.000
we will suffer from unreliability.

57:16.000 --> 57:21.000
Again, like any way out of any situation,

57:21.000 --> 57:27.000
here the way out is only in the optimal combination of volume and reliability.

57:27.000 --> 57:33.000
It makes sense not to read the sources nearby,

57:33.000 --> 57:39.000
but to read the sources that take the opposite positions.

57:39.000 --> 57:43.000
Then this picture may be more objective.

57:43.000 --> 57:45.000
The next phenomenon.

57:45.000 --> 57:50.000
The popular content analysis today does not have a definite interpretation.

57:50.000 --> 57:53.000
What does this mean for us?

57:53.000 --> 57:57.000
The concept of content analysis came from psychology.

57:57.000 --> 58:01.000
And sociology still does not have a definite definition,

58:01.000 --> 58:03.000
it is not formalized.

58:03.000 --> 58:06.000
Therefore, everyone talks about their own content analysis.

58:06.000 --> 58:12.000
Someone in this concept invests completely different mechanisms, different methods.

58:13.000 --> 58:21.000
Accordingly, one content analysis will not be connected with another.

58:21.000 --> 58:26.000
Every time we will have to invent a bicycle.

58:26.000 --> 58:31.000
Because there is still no single understanding of what a single mechanism is.

58:31.000 --> 58:34.000
So, what can we do?

58:34.000 --> 58:38.000
What are the effective technologies of work

58:38.000 --> 58:42.000
with a growing flow of unstructured text information?

58:42.000 --> 58:46.000
When we talk about searching for information on the Internet

58:46.000 --> 58:48.000
with large information arrays,

58:48.000 --> 58:50.000
we have two criteria.

58:50.000 --> 58:52.000
The first criterion is the size of the database,

58:52.000 --> 58:55.000
the number of sites it attracted.

58:55.000 --> 59:00.000
And, accordingly, the larger the database,

59:00.000 --> 59:04.000
the more sites the search engine knows.

59:04.000 --> 59:06.000
And the more accurate the search.

59:06.000 --> 59:09.000
And the second criterion is the information of the given links.

59:09.000 --> 59:13.000
That is, not only to attract many sites,

59:13.000 --> 59:19.000
but also the information contained in these links should be useful to you.

59:19.000 --> 59:22.000
So, what are the main criteria we should consider

59:22.000 --> 59:25.000
when we search and sort documents from sites?

59:25.000 --> 59:28.000
First, the number of searchable words in the text,

59:28.000 --> 59:30.000
the distance between these words in the text,

59:30.000 --> 59:35.000
the place in the text where these words are found in the title, in the text itself,

59:35.000 --> 59:38.000
the appearance of the font used,

59:38.000 --> 59:41.000
and the number of links from the Internet to this document.

59:41.000 --> 59:45.000
These are the criteria that will help us sort documents.

59:53.000 --> 59:59.000
When we talk about who needs information in the company,

59:59.000 --> 01:00:04.000
it is difficult to select an employee

01:00:04.000 --> 01:00:10.000
who would never use some external, unstructured information.

01:00:10.000 --> 01:00:12.000
I think that every employee,

01:00:12.000 --> 01:00:17.000
well, we will not take such service staff as a cleaner,

01:00:17.000 --> 01:00:21.000
we take the manager's position and higher,

01:00:21.000 --> 01:00:27.000
then, of course, all these positions use unstructured information from the Internet

01:00:27.000 --> 01:00:30.000
for their goals, for making their decisions,

01:00:30.000 --> 01:00:33.000
for analyzing the existing situation, and so on.

01:00:33.000 --> 01:00:39.000
But here are some examples of such specialists.

01:00:39.000 --> 01:00:43.000
For security services, it is especially relevant

01:00:43.000 --> 01:00:46.000
to analyze the reliability of new partners and the environment,

01:00:46.000 --> 01:00:49.000
monitoring the state of permanent partners and their projects,

01:00:49.000 --> 01:00:53.000
assessment and forecast of the company's development,

01:00:53.000 --> 01:00:55.000
risk assessment and forecast.

01:00:55.000 --> 01:00:58.000
Here is a very important remark.

01:00:58.000 --> 01:01:06.000
Why is it important for security services to be able to use all this unstructured information?

01:01:06.000 --> 01:01:12.000
Because, as you know, about 30% of confidential and about 10% of very confidential,

01:01:12.000 --> 01:01:15.000
completely secret information is contained in open sources.

01:01:15.000 --> 01:01:19.000
As an example, we can cite the book by Viktor Suvorov,

01:01:19.000 --> 01:01:24.000
which described the peculiarities of Stalin's policy,

01:01:24.000 --> 01:01:27.000
based only on newspaper sources.

01:01:27.000 --> 01:01:32.000
He specifically wrote in the preface that he did not use any secret document,

01:01:32.000 --> 01:01:39.000
he used only the information that was written in Soviet newspapers.

01:01:39.000 --> 01:01:43.000
And based on this, he made his conclusions.

01:01:43.000 --> 01:01:47.000
Here you can argue about the legitimacy of these conclusions or not,

01:01:47.000 --> 01:01:54.000
but the fact is that this book is a very good illustration,

01:01:54.000 --> 01:02:01.000
a confirmation that completely secret information is also contained in open sources.

01:02:01.000 --> 01:02:07.000
Therefore, it is very important for your security service to be able to work with information,

01:02:07.000 --> 01:02:13.000
to be able to predict, analyze, to identify the main thing

01:02:14.000 --> 01:02:23.000
and pay attention to the nuances that will help to predict events with the greatest probability.

01:02:27.000 --> 01:02:29.000
Who else is it important for?

01:02:29.000 --> 01:02:32.000
I will repeat that it is important for everyone to work with information.

01:02:32.000 --> 01:02:36.000
Here is an example for the department of strategic planning and management.

01:02:36.000 --> 01:02:42.000
It is important to analyze the activities of the enterprise, macroeconomic analysis,

01:02:42.000 --> 01:02:45.000
and the predicted state of the country.

01:02:45.000 --> 01:02:50.000
It is very important here, because, as we did not want,

01:02:50.000 --> 01:02:54.000
but all internal political events, even external political events,

01:02:54.000 --> 01:02:58.000
they sometimes have a great impact on the life of the company,

01:02:58.000 --> 01:03:02.000
and its survivability in certain conditions.

01:03:03.000 --> 01:03:09.000
And since competent analysts who deal with strategic management,

01:03:09.000 --> 01:03:13.000
they must, based on the information they receive, build forecasts,

01:03:13.000 --> 01:03:15.000
this is their main function,

01:03:15.000 --> 01:03:24.000
then they must understand the tendencies of development in the geopolitical situation,

01:03:25.000 --> 01:03:32.000
and how it can affect the life of a particular company.

01:03:33.000 --> 01:03:39.000
Next, analysis of the market segment, monitoring of competitors is an important tool.

01:03:39.000 --> 01:03:44.000
Expansion and diversification of business influence,

01:03:44.000 --> 01:03:48.000
development of optimal marketing and business strategies.

01:03:49.000 --> 01:03:56.000
This is the information, unstructured stream of information,

01:03:56.000 --> 01:04:02.000
which they receive from all sorts of sources, will allow them to solve such tasks.

